Title : Alexander Clifford Beauglehole
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}
'''Alexander Clifford (Cliff) Beauglehole''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|OAM}} (26 August 1920 â€“ 19 January 2002) was an Australian farmer, [[botany|botanist]], [[Plant collecting|plant collector]] and [[natural history|naturalist]].

==Life==
Beauglehole was born in Gorae West, a rural locality near [[Portland, Victoria|Portland]] in the [[Shire of Glenelg]], in south-western [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. He attended Gorae state primary school but left after attaining his Qualifying Certificate to help his parents on the farm. He soon began making botanical surveys of the Portland area, as well as engaging in other natural history activities such as the study of [[Australian native bees]], surveys of bone deposits in caves and the examination of beach-washed [[seabird]]s.<ref name=eas/><ref name=wgr/>

In the 1940s he discovered a new [[Stylidium|triggerplant]] species, ''[[Stylidium beaugleholei]]'', and set up a herbarium which grew to eventually contain over 23,000 specimens. Beauglehole continued to work the family farm until 1968, after which contracting to carry out botanical surveys in [[national park]]s and for the Victorian Land Conservation Council became his principal occupation. He published on a wide variety of natural history subjects. From 1979 to 1984 he produced 13 volumes of ''The Distribution and Conservation of Vascular Plants in Victoria'', written to cover the 73 study areas of the Victorian Conservation Council.<ref name=eas>{{cite web |url= http://www.eoas.info/biogs/P000214b.htm |title= Beauglehole, Alexander Clifford (1920 - 2002) |accessdate=2014-04-28 |work= |first=GJ |last=McCarthy |publisher= Encyclopedia of Australian Science |date=2004-09-10 }}</ref><ref name=wgr>{{cite web |url= http://www.austehc.unimelb.edu.au/guides/will/WILL004.htm |title= Alexander Clifford Beauglehole |accessdate=2014-04-28 |work= James Hamlyn Willis Guide to Records |first= |last= |publisher= Australian Science and Technology Heritage Centre |date=2007-11-15 }}</ref>

==Honours and awards==
* [[Australian Natural History Medallion]] (1971)
* Honorary Member of the [[Field Naturalists Club of Victoria]] (1982)
* Medal of the [[Order of Australia]] (OAM) (1984)

